Side QR of a ∆PQR has been produced to the point S. If ∠PRS = 115° and ∠P = 45°,
then ∠Q is equal to,
(a) 70° (b) 105° (c) 51° (d) 80°

In an equilateral triangle ABC, if AD is an altitude then 4AD2 is equal to
(a) 2BD2 (b) BC2 (c) 3AB2 (d) 2DC2

PS is the bisector of ∠P and PQ = PR. Then ∆PRS and ∆PQS are congruent by the
criterion
(a) AAA (b) SAS (c) ASA (d) both (b) and (c)

3 times the measure of an angle is 14 less than the measure of its complement. What is
the measure of the angle?
(a) 19° (b) 57° (c) 71° (d) 76°

Two angles are congruent and complementary. What is the measure of each angle?
(a) 180 0 (b) 900 (c) 450 (d) 3600

The measure of the supplement of an angle is 12 more than twice the measure of the
angle. What is the measure of the angle?
(a)124 (b). 48
(c) 56 (d) 24

In triangle ABC, if BC = 3 and AC = 4, then what is the length of segment CD?
(a) 3 (b). 15/4 (c) 5 (d). 16/3

In triangle ABC, angle A=90°, angle B=30°, BC=8cm. Find the length of side AB
and AC?
(a) 4, 6.93 (b) 5, 5.964 (c) 7, 4.675 (d) 8, 3.876

In ∆ ABC is an isosceles triangle and ∠ B = 65o , find x.
(a) 60 o (b) 70 o (c) 50 o (d) none of these

In a triangle, one angle is of 90°. Then
(i) The other two angles are of 45° each
(ii) In remaining two angles, one angle is 90° and other is 45°
(iii) Remaining two angles are complementary
In the given option(s) which is true?
(a) (i) only (b) (ii) only (c) (iii) only (d) (i) and (ii)

If in an isosceles triangle, each of the base angles is 40°, then the triangle is
(a) Right-angled triangle (b) Acute angled triangle
(c) Obtuse angled triangle (d) Isosceles right-angled triangle

In Fig., BC = CA and ∠A = 40. Then, ∠ACD is equal
to (a) 40° (b) 80° (c) 120° (d)
60°
Prove that angles opposite to equal sides of an isosceles triangle are equal.

In the given figure, AD is bisector of ∠BAC and ∠CPD = ∠BPD. Prove that ΔCAP ≌
ΔBAP.

The exterior angles, obtained on producing the base of a triangle both way
are 1040 and 1360 . Find all the angles of the triangle.

In a triangle ABC, E and F respectively are mid-points of equal sides AB and AC of
ΔABC. Show that BF = CE.
AD is an altitude of an isosceles ΔABC in which AB = AC. Show that AD bisects BC.

In a ΔABC, the internal bisectors of B and C meet at P and the external
bisectors od B and C meet at Q. Prove that BPC + BQC = 1800.

In the given figure, triangles PQC and PRC are such that QC = PR and PQ = CR.
Prove that ∠PCQ = ∠CPR.

In the given figure, AB = AD, AC = AE and ∠BAD = ∠EAC, then prove that BC =
DE.
